finally

PRAKASH KUMAR

12 September 2018

Reading the Dataset

azd <- read.csv('azd.csv',stringsAsFactors = F)

Converting a priceDate column into the date column

azd$priceDate = as.Date(azd$priceDate)

Creating a regular date from 2005-04-11 to 2018-08-31

mydates = seq.Date(from = as.Date("2005-04-11"), 
                   to = as.Date("2018-08-31"), 
                   by = 1)

Converting to a data frame (required for the merge)

mydates = data.frame(priceDate = mydates)

Padding with ‘mydates’

data = merge(azd, mydates, by = "priceDate", all.y = T)

Removing sundays, because market remains close on sundays

data = data[-(seq(from = 7, to = nrow(data), by = 7)),]

Selecting only the price or target columns and Converting into time series data type

pdata <- data[,c(8,9,10)]
pdata = ts(pdata,frequency = 6)

NA imputation through na.klaman in the dataset

pdatam <- na.kalman(pdata, model ="StructTS", smooth = TRUE, type ="trend")

Dividing the data into train and test for checking which alogrithm is better in terms of different metrics

train <- head(pdatam,4214)
test <- tail(pdatam,30)

Predicting the minPrice , maxPrice & modalPrice and calculating the root mean square error(RMSE) for comparing the model

minPrice column forecasting and calculating the RMSE value by different time Series algorithms

through neural net by nnetar()

nnet_model <- nnetar(train[,1])
min_nnet <- forecast(nnet_model, h= 30, PI = T)

### measuring the root mean square error and MAPE
min_price_nnet <- sqrt(sum((min_nnet$mean - test[,1])^2)/30)
min_nnt_mape <- accuracy(min_nnet$mean,test[,1])

Upon analysing the metrics performance of various models, it was found that ETS model performed better compared to NNETAR and ARIMA models

Therefore, for predicting the 30 days it is better to use the ETS model
